---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "About Found in Pi";
const description =
  "Found in Pi is a tiny internet toy for turning images into honest, shareable pi relics.";
const canonical = new URL("/about", Astro.url.origin).toString();
const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  name: title,
  description,
  url: canonical
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <main class="about-shell">
    <nav class="about-nav" aria-label="About page">
      <a href="/" class="wordmark">Found in Pi</a>
      <div class="header-links">
        <a class="primary-link secondary" href="/museum">Museum</a>
        <a class="primary-link" href="/">Try it</a>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <section class="about-hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>A dumb, honest toy about finding pictures in pi.</h1>
      <p>
        Found in Pi is a fun product built around an old internet joke: if every
        file is somewhere in pi, can you store anything for free?
      </p>
      <p>
        The real answer is no. So this does not pretend to do that. You upload
        an image, the site searches a finite chunk of pi, and it redraws your
        image from the closest fragments it can find there.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="about-grid" aria-label="What Found in Pi does">
      <article>
        <h2>What it does</h2>
        <p>
          It breaks your image into small tiles, looks for pi fragments that
          roughly match those tiles, and makes a new image out of those matches.
          Then it gives the result a name, a score, and a shareable page.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>What it does not do</h2>
        <p>
          It does not search all of pi. It does not compress your file into pi.
          It does not prove your image was always waiting there. That would be
          funny, but it would also be fake.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>Why the score exists</h2>
        <p>
          The score is just a way to compare results inside this site. Some
          images fit the current dig site better than others. That is the whole
          game.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>Why publish</h2>
        <p>
          Good results can live in the museum. The more a relic is viewed, the
          higher it can show up. It is meant to be something you can post, send
          to a friend, or stumble into from the random page.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="about-note">
      <h2>The honesty contract</h2>
      <p>
        Found in Pi searches declared dig sites. Dig Site I is the fast default.
        Dig Site II searches deeper. Every relic says which one it used, how
        many digits were searched, and which index version produced it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The product is more interesting when the limits are visible. The point
        is not to fake magic. The point is to make a weird little artifact and
        show the receipt.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="about-cta">
      <a class="primary-link" href="/">Make a relic</a>
      <a class="primary-link secondary" href="/random">Open random</a>
      <a class="plain-link" href="https://x.com/caffe1neduck" rel="noreferrer">
        built by @caffe1neduck
      </a>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
